Review: Well aware I’m way too old to be seeing this all the way through for the first time (other blind spots of note: Apocalypse Now, Seven Samurai, etc but none more urgent than this)…a thrilling series of aha moments realizing why that girl I knew in highschool was like that. I suppose she pulled it off, but she’s no Regina George.

Not to be too insufferable, but I got a blu-ray player for Christmas and figured I’d pick this up in an effort to make a good-faith foray into Godard’s work. Lyrical and drenched in splotches of vibrant primary colors, this rings of one’s (Godard’s) frustrated entanglement of intellect and emotion. It’s equal parts lovely to look at and difficult to comprehend, but I was nonetheless won over by the time the final tragicomic sequence rolls around. What a trip!

The present unto which May December, Haynes’ latest, arrives feels particularly elusive—and, fittingly, so does the film. Written by Samy Burch and loosely inspired by the public scandal surrounding Mary Kay Letourneau, the screenplay orbits three central characters: Gracie Atherton-Yoo (Julianne Moore), a suburban pariah who was once the subject of a tabloid frenzy surrounding her predatory sexual involvement with a 13-year-old boy; Joe Atherton-Yoo (Charles Melton), the boy, now in his 30s and married with children to Gracie; and…
